# arvo-hash — backlog

> **Type-surface reminder**: new entries use `arvo::USize` /
> `Bool` / `UFixed<N, 0, S>` instead of `usize` / `bool` / `u*`;
> `notko::Maybe` / `Outcome` instead of `Option` / `Result`. See
> `rules/type-surface.md`.

## Named width aliases for Fnv1a

`Fnv1a<const N: BitWidth>` ships in DESIGN. Named aliases for common
widths land if consumer call sites get verbose:

```rust
pub type Fnv1a28 = Fnv1a<{ width_of(28) }>;
pub type Fnv1a32 = Fnv1a<{ width_of(32) }>;
pub type Fnv1a64 = Fnv1a<{ width_of(64) }>;
```

Today consumers instantiate at any width directly via the const-generic
parameter; named aliases are pure ergonomic sugar and not yet earned.

## Other concrete algorithms

Shipping order as consumers surface need:

- XxHash64: when a faster non-cryptographic hash is wanted.
- Crc32: when checksum use cases surface (vehje bytecode integrity,
  persistence file checksumming).

Each concrete algorithm lands as a unit struct implementing
`Hasher<N>`. `HasherExt<N>::hash` falls out via the blanket impl.

## Hilavitkutin-str migration

hilavitkutin-str's existing `const_fnv1a` predates arvo-hash's
concrete `Fnv1a<N>` ship. Migrate hilavitkutin-str's `Str` interning
hash path to call `Fnv1a::<{ width_of(28) }>::hash_const(...)`,
remove the local FNV implementation, and re-export from arvo-hash
where appropriate. Tracked in hilavitkutin-side task #181.

## Wider bit widths

If arvo-bits grows u128 backing for Bits (its own BACKLOG item),
arvo-hash gains Hash128-domain semantic aliases.

## Cryptographic hashes

Out of scope. arvo-hash targets non-cryptographic identity hashes.
A sibling arvo-crypto crate may appear if cryptographic hash
needs surface.

## Semantic aliases

NameHash, KeyHash, or similar named aliases beyond ContentHash
land once consumer patterns stabilise. The starting form is a
local alias in the consuming crate over ContentHash or Bits<N>;
promotion happens when a second consumer shares the alias.
